<section xml:id="section-assignment-week5">
  <title>Week 5 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the dimensions of these spans. (12)
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li><me>
          \Span \left \{
            \begin{pmatrix}
              0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 
            \end{pmatrix},
            \begin{pmatrix}
              3 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 2
            \end{pmatrix},
            \begin{pmatrix}
              4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ -1
            \end{pmatrix},
            \begin{pmatrix}
              1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ -2
            \end{pmatrix},
          \right\}
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \Span \left \{
            \begin{pmatrix}
              1 \\ -1 \\ 2 
            \end{pmatrix},
            \begin{pmatrix}
              3 \\ 1 \\ 1
            \end{pmatrix},
            \begin{pmatrix}
              -1 \\ -2 \\ 3
            \end{pmatrix},
            \begin{pmatrix}
              6 \\ -1 \\ -1 
            \end{pmatrix},
          \right\}
        </me></li>
        <li><me>
          \Span \left \{
            \begin{pmatrix}
              1 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ -1 
            \end{pmatrix},
            \begin{pmatrix}
              0 \\ 1 \\ -1 \\ -1 \\ -1
            \end{pmatrix},
            \begin{pmatrix}
              0 \\ - \\ 1 \\ -1 \\ -1 
            \end{pmatrix}
          \right\}
        </me></li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the dimension of these loci. (12)
      </p>
      <p><ol>
        <li>
          The locus of the equations <m>w - x - y + z = 0</m> and
          <m>2w + y + z = 3</m> in <m>\RR^4</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
          The locus of the equations <m>x + y - z = 0</m> and <m>2x - 2y 
          - z = 2</m> in <m>\RR^3</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
          The locus of the equations <m>w - z = 0</m>, <m>w - x
          = 0</m>, and <m>w - y = 0</m> in <m>\RR^4</m>.
        </li>
      </ol></p>
    </li>
    <li>
      Let <m>u</m>, <m>v</m>, and <m>w</m> be vectors in
      <m>\RR^4</m>. Prove that <m>u</m>, <m>v</m>, and <m>w</m> are
      linearily independent if and only if there is a unique
      direction (a unique non-zero vector up to scaling) that is
      perpendicular to all three vectors. (Remember this is an `if
      and only if' proof, so do both directions of implication.) (6) 
    </li>
  </ol></p>
